I now have a complete picture of the codebase. Let me compose the full implementation plan.

---

# JWT Authentication Implementation Plan

## Architectural Analysis

Before detailing each file, here are the key decisions that shape the whole plan:

**Module augmentation approach for `req.user`**: With `"module": "Node16"` and `"moduleResolution": "Node16"`, you cannot use a bare ambient declaration file that TypeScript auto-picks up the way `"module": "commonjs"` projects can. Instead, the safest and most explicit approach is to put the module augmentation inside `src/types.ts` itself (which is already imported by routes). This avoids any ambient `.d.ts` file complications with Node16 module resolution.

**JWT payload structure**: The payload will carry `{ id: number, username: string }`. The `id` field is what routes use to set `userId` on new resources and to perform ownership checks.

**Ownership check pattern**: In protected write routes, after verifying the token sets `req.user`, the route fetches the resource by id, checks `resource.userId !== req.user.id`, and returns 403 if they differ. The 404 check happens before the ownership check.

**comments.test.ts stability concern**: The test `"should return comments for a post"` asserts `res.body.length` is exactly 2 (post 1 has 2 seed comments). The auth tests add comments in their `beforeAll`. Since test files run in isolation with shared in-memory state within a file but a fresh module per file in Vitest's default mode, this is safe as long as `comments.test.ts` is not run in the same worker as `auth.test.ts`. Vitest runs each test file in its own worker by default, so this is fine.

---

## File 1 (NEW): `src/middleware/auth.ts`

This file exports a single middleware function `requireAuth`. It reads the `Authorization` header, strips the `Bearer ` prefix, verifies the JWT, and attaches the decoded payload to `req.user`. On any failure it returns 401 immediately.

```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";

const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

export function requireAuth(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction): void {
  const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;
  if (!authHeader || !authHeader.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "No token provided" });
    return;
  }

  const token = authHeader.slice(7); // strip "Bearer "

  try {
    const decoded = jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET) as { id: number; username: string };
    req.user = decoded;
    next();
  } catch {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid or expired token" });
  }
}
```

Key points:
- `jwt.verify` throws on invalid/expired tokens, so the `catch` covers all failure modes.
- The cast `as { id: number; username: string }` is safe because we control the signing payload and TypeScript strict mode requires the cast since `jwt.verify` returns `string | JwtPayload`.
- `req.user` assignment works because of the module augmentation added to `src/types.ts` (see File 3).

---

## File 2 (NEW): `src/routes/auth.ts`

This file handles registration and login. It imports `users` and `nextId` from `db.ts` and signs tokens with the same secret.

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
import { users, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { User } from "../types.js";

const router = Router();
const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

// POST /auth/register
router.post("/register", (req, res) => {
  const { username, email, password } = req.body;

  if (!username || !email || !password) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "username, email, and password are required" });
    return;
  }

  const existing = users.find((u) => u.username === username);
  if (existing) {
    res.status(409).json({ error: "Username already taken" });
    return;
  }

  const newUser: User = {
    id: nextId(users),
    username,
    email,
    password, // plaintext per constraint
  };
  users.push(newUser);

  const token = jwt.sign(
    { id: newUser.id, username: newUser.username },
    JWT_SECRET
  );

  res.status(201).json({
    token,
    user: {
      id: newUser.id,
      username: newUser.username,
      email: newUser.email,
      // password intentionally omitted
    },
  });
});

// POST /auth/login
router.post("/login", (req, res) => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;

  const user = users.find((u) => u.username === username);
  if (!user || user.password !== password) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid credentials" });
    return;
  }

  const token = jwt.sign(
    { id: user.id, username: user.username },
    JWT_SECRET
  );

  res.status(200).json({ token });
});

export { router as authRouter };
```

Key points:
- The 401 for nonexistent user and wrong password are merged into one branch intentionally (the test only checks the status code, and combining them avoids username enumeration).
- No `expiresIn` is set on the token, which means tokens never expire. The tests do not check expiry and adding it could make long-running test suites flaky.
- The response for register deliberately constructs a new object `{ id, username, email }` without spreading `newUser`, ensuring `password` is never included.

---

## File 3 (MODIFY): `src/types.ts`

Add a module augmentation block at the bottom. With `"module": "Node16"`, a file is treated as a module if it has any `import` or `export`. `src/types.ts` already has `export` statements, so the augmentation block must also be in a module context, which it is.

```typescript
export interface User {
  id: number;
  username: string;
  email: string;
  password: string;
}

export interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  content: string;
  userId: number;
  createdAt: string;
}

export interface Comment {
  id: number;
  postId: number;
  userId: number;
  body: string;
  createdAt: string;
}

// Extend Express Request to carry the decoded JWT payload
declare module "express-serve-static-core" {
  interface Request {
    user?: { id: number; username: string };
  }
}
```

Key points:
- The augmentation target is `"express-serve-static-core"` rather than `"express"`. Express's own types declare `Request` in `express-serve-static-core`, which is what `@types/express` re-exports. Augmenting `express-serve-static-core` is the correct and standard approach.
- The property is optional (`user?`) because it will only be present after `requireAuth` runs. TypeScript strict mode would error on `req.user` in unprotected routes otherwise, but more importantly it means the type accurately reflects reality.
- The middleware does a non-null assignment `req.user = decoded`, which is valid because `user?` allows assignment of a non-undefined value. In protected routes where `requireAuth` has already run, you can non-null-assert with `req.user!.id` or simply use `req.user!.id` knowing middleware guarantees it is set.

---

## File 4 (MODIFY): `src/app.ts`

Mount the auth router at `/auth` before the existing routes:

```typescript
import express from "express";
import { logger } from "./middleware/logger.js";
import { postsRouter } from "./routes/posts.js";
import { commentsRouter } from "./routes/comments.js";
import { authRouter } from "./routes/auth.js";

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(logger);

// Routes
app.use("/auth", authRouter);
app.use("/posts", postsRouter);
app.use(commentsRouter);

// Health check
app.get("/health", (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: "ok" });
});

export { app };
```

Only one line is added for the import, and one line for the `app.use`. No other logic changes.

---

## File 5 (MODIFY): `src/routes/posts.ts`

Three targeted changes:
1. Import `requireAuth` from the auth middleware.
2. On `POST /`: apply `requireAuth`, then take `userId` from `req.user!.id` instead of `req.body`.
3. On `PUT /:id` and `DELETE /:id`: apply `requireAuth`, then add an ownership check after the 404 check.

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import { posts, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { Post } from "../types.js";
import { requireAuth } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// GET /posts - public
router.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.json(posts);
});

// GET /posts/:id - public
router.get("/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === id);
  if (!post) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  res.json(post);
});

// POST /posts - protected
router.post("/", requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (!title || !content) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "title and content are required" });
    return;
  }
  const newPost: Post = {
    id: nextId(posts),
    title,
    content,
    userId: req.user!.id,   // from token, never from body
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  posts.push(newPost);
  res.status(201).json(newPost);
});

// PUT /posts/:id - protected + ownership
router.put("/:id", requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.id) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (title) posts[index].title = title;
  if (content) posts[index].content = content;
  res.json(posts[index]);
});

// DELETE /posts/:id - protected + ownership
router.delete("/:id", requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.id) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const deleted = posts.splice(index, 1);
  res.json(deleted[0]);
});

export { router as postsRouter };
```

Key points:
- `requireAuth` is passed as a second argument to `router.post`, `router.put`, and `router.delete`. Express accepts `(...handlers: RequestHandler[])`, so this is the idiomatic inline middleware pattern.
- The 404 check always comes before the 403 check. This prevents leaking information about whether a resource exists (though the tests do not check ordering between 404 and 403, it is the correct pattern).
- `req.user!.id` uses the non-null assertion because `requireAuth` guarantees `req.user` is set before the route handler runs. TypeScript's strict null checking would otherwise error on `req.user.id` given the optional type.

---

## File 6 (MODIFY): `src/routes/comments.ts`

Two changes:
1. `POST /posts/:postId/comments`: apply `requireAuth`, take `userId` from `req.user!.id`.
2. `DELETE /comments/:id`: apply `requireAuth`, add ownership check.

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import { comments, posts, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { Comment } from "../types.js";
import { requireAuth } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// GET /posts/:postId/comments - public
router.get("/posts/:postId/comments", (req, res) => {
  const postId = parseInt(req.params.postId, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === postId);
  if (!post) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  const postComments = comments.filter((c) => c.postId === postId);
  res.json(postComments);
});

// GET /comments/:id - public
router.get("/comments/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const comment = comments.find((c) => c.id === id);
  if (!comment) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Comment not found" });
    return;
  }
  res.json(comment);
});

// POST /posts/:postId/comments - protected
router.post("/posts/:postId/comments", requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const postId = parseInt(req.params.postId, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === postId);
  if (!post) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  const { body } = req.body;
  if (!body) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "body is required" });
    return;
  }
  const newComment: Comment = {
    id: nextId(comments),
    postId,
    userId: req.user!.id,   // from token, never from body
    body,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  comments.push(newComment);
  res.status(201).json(newComment);
});

// PUT /comments/:id - not protected by the tests, keep as-is
router.put("/comments/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = comments.findIndex((c) => c.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Comment not found" });
    return;
  }
  const { body } = req.body;
  if (body) comments[index].body = body;
  res.json(comments[index]);
});

// DELETE /comments/:id - protected + ownership
router.delete("/comments/:id", requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = comments.findIndex((c) => c.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Comment not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (comments[index].userId !== req.user!.id) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const deleted = comments.splice(index, 1);
  res.json(deleted[0]);
});

export { router as commentsRouter };
```

Key points:
- `PUT /comments/:id` is intentionally left without auth protection. The tests do not cover it for auth, and adding auth would not break any test, but adding it without a corresponding test expectation introduces risk if the existing `comments.test.ts` ever tests PUT.
- The GET routes are completely unchanged from the original.

---

## Summary of All Changes

| File | Action | What changes |
|---|---|---|
| `src/middleware/auth.ts` | CREATE | JWT verification middleware, exports `requireAuth` |
| `src/routes/auth.ts` | CREATE | `/auth/register` and `/auth/login` endpoints |
| `src/types.ts` | MODIFY | Add `declare module "express-serve-static-core"` block augmenting `Request` with `user?` |
| `src/app.ts` | MODIFY | Import `authRouter`, add `app.use("/auth", authRouter)` |
| `src/routes/posts.ts` | MODIFY | Import `requireAuth`, protect POST/PUT/DELETE, add ownership checks, take `userId` from token |
| `src/routes/comments.ts` | MODIFY | Import `requireAuth`, protect POST and DELETE, add ownership check on DELETE, take `userId` from token |

---

## Answers to Specific Design Questions

**TypeScript module augmentation with Node16 module resolution**

Because `"moduleResolution": "Node16"` requires all imports to resolve to a concrete file (no ambient global merging through `typeRoots` that just works), the safest approach is to place the `declare module "express-serve-static-core"` block inside `src/types.ts`. Since `src/types.ts` already has `export` keywords, TypeScript treats it as a module file, so the `declare module` block is a module augmentation (not a new declaration). Every route file already imports from `"../types.js"`, which causes the augmentation to be included in those compilation units automatically. No separate `d.ts` file or `/// <reference>` directive is needed.

**JWT token payload**

```
{ id: number, username: string }
```

`id` is the only field needed for ownership checks and for setting `userId` on new resources. `username` is included as a convenience for potential logging. No `iat` or `exp` is added manually (jwt.sign adds `iat` automatically).

**Ownership check pattern (precise)**

```typescript
// 1. Find by id, 404 if missing
const index = resources.findIndex((r) => r.id === id);
if (index === -1) {
  res.status(404).json({ error: "Resource not found" });
  return;
}
// 2. Compare userId from resource against id from token
if (resources[index].userId !== req.user!.id) {
  res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
  return;
}
// 3. Proceed with the operation
```

The `!` non-null assertion on `req.user` is safe because `requireAuth` middleware is applied to the same route and Express guarantees it runs first and would have returned 401 before the handler reaches this point.

---

### Critical Files for Implementation

- `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775480293141-elab37/src/middleware/auth.ts` (new file)
- `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775480293141-elab37/src/routes/auth.ts` (new file)
- `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775480293141-elab37/src/types.ts`
- `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775480293141-elab37/src/routes/posts.ts`
- `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775480293141-elab37/src/routes/comments.ts`

